{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1775862452628,"sessionID":"ses_28659db9ffferpMTMlg4pOfnhF","part":{"id":"prt_d79a6918a001OxT9GP44f5SnJr","messageID":"msg_d79a68af4001RT63YOoxnk3AWu","sessionID":"ses_28659db9ffferpMTMlg4pOfnhF","snapshot":"f33c5114db06c230ebdbad281b75532a26b6f114","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775862457670,"sessionID":"ses_28659db9ffferpMTMlg4pOfnhF","part":{"id":"prt_d79a693ed001XHzesdYqotaQtB","messageID":"msg_d79a68af4001RT63YOoxnk3AWu","sessionID":"ses_28659db9ffferpMTMlg4pOfnhF","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"toolu_fff261ad32014e68851c0d31","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-qwen3.5-plus_20260410T163217Z/AR-017-proposal.md"},"output":"<path>/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-qwen3.5-plus_20260410T163217Z/AR-017-proposal.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # AR-017: PicoD JWT Middleware\n2: \n3: ## Purpose\n4: \n5: This proposal implements JWT (JSON Web Token) authentication middleware for the PicoD HTTP daemon in the `pkg/picod` module. The goal is to:\n6: \n7: 1. **Secure API Access** - Protect PicoD HTTP endpoints with RSA-based JWT authentication\n8: 2. **Token Validation** - Validate JWT tokens signed with RSA private keys using the corresponding public key\n9: 3. **Request Authorization** - Intercept and authenticate incoming HTTP requests before allowing access to command execution APIs\n10: 4. **Flexible Configuration** - Support configuration via environment variables and command-line flags\n11: 5. **Health Endpoint Protection** - Optionally protect the health check endpoint with JWT authentication\n12: \n13: This implementation builds upon the PicoD execution infrastructure established in AR-015 and provides the security layer required for multi-tenant code interpreter deployments.\n14: \n15: ## Scope\n16: \n17: **Module:** `pkg/picod`  \n18: **Language:** Go  \n19: **Size:** S\n20: \n21: This AR covers:\n22: \n23: - **In scope:**\n24:   - JWT middleware implementation (`middleware.go`)\n25:   - JWT token validation logic (`jwt.go`)\n26:   - RSA key handling utilities (`crypto.go`)\n27:   - Configuration via environment variables and flags\n28:   - Unit tests with mocked tokens and keys\n29:   - Integration tests with real HTTP server\n30:   - Error handling and logging\n31: \n32: - **Out of scope:**\n33:   - JWT token generation (handled by external auth service)\n34:   - Token refresh mechanisms\n35:   - User/role-based authorization (only authentication)\n36:   - OAuth2 or other authentication protocols\n37:   - Session management (covered in AR-013)\n38:   - PicoD HTTP server implementation (covered in `code-execution/` specs)\n39: \n40: ## Current State Analysis\n41: \n42: ### Existing PicoD Infrastructure\n43: \n44: The current PicoD system has command execution infrastructure:\n45: \n46: 1. **PicoD Core** (`pkg/picod/picod.go`):\n47:    - Main `PicoD` struct with sandbox ID, work directory, limits, and security options\n48:    - Functional options pattern for configuration\n49:    - Structured logging with klog\n50: \n51: 2. **Command Execution** (`pkg/picod/executor.go`):\n52:    - `Run()` and `Start()` methods for command execution\n53:    - Resource limit enforcement (timeout, CPU, memory, output size)\n54:    - Output capture and streaming\n55: \n56: 3. **Security Module** (`pkg/picod/security.go`):\n57:    - Command validation and path safety checks\n58:    - Privilege dropping and capability management\n59:    - Allowlist-based command selection\n60: \n61: 4. **Configuration** (`pkg/picod/config.go`):\n62:    - Environment variable loading\n63:    - Default values for resource limits\n64: \n65: ### Gaps Identified\n66: \n67: 1. **No HTTP authentication** - PicoD HTTP daemon has no authentication layer\n68: 2. **No JWT validation** - Cannot validate JWT tokens from incoming requests\n69: 3. **No RSA key handling** - Missing utilities for loading and using RSA public keys\n70: 4. **No middleware pattern** - No HTTP middleware for request interception\n71: 5. **Health endpoint exposed** - Health check endpoint is publicly accessible\n72: \n73: ### PicoD HTTP Context\n74: \n75: Per `code-execution/design.md` and `code-execution/spec.md`:\n76: - PicoD is an HTTP daemon that runs commands inside a configurable workspace jail\n77: - Exposes health endpoint with JWT (RSA)-protected APIs\n78: - CLI flags: `-port` (default 8080), `-workspace` (default: current working directory)\n79: - Server uses `ReadHeaderTimeout` of 10 seconds\n80: - Authentication modes: `picod` (JWT required) or `none` (no auth)\n81: \n82: ### Kubernetes Client-Go Context\n83: \n84: Per `deployment/client-go.md`:\n85: - Generated Kubernetes client for `runtime.agentcube.volcano.sh/v1alpha1`\n86: - `CodeInterpreter` CRD supports `AuthMode` enum (`picod` or `none`)\n87: - Workload manager injects `PICOD_AUTH_PUBLIC_KEY` when `AuthMode=picod`\n88: - Public key provided as base64-encoded PEM string\n89: \n90: ## Proposed Changes\n91: \n92: ### 1. JWT Middleware (`middleware.go`)\n93: \n94: ```go\n95: // JWTMiddleware is HTTP middleware that validates JWT tokens\n96: type JWTMiddleware struct {\n97:     // publicKey is the RSA public key for token validation\n98:     publicKey *rsa.PublicKey\n99:     \n100:     // skipPaths is a list of paths to skip authentication\n101:     skipPaths map[string]bool\n102:     \n103:     // logger is the structured logger\n104:     logger klog.Logger\n105: }\n106: \n107: // NewJWTMiddleware creates a new JWT middleware\n108: func NewJWTMiddleware(publicKey *rsa.PublicKey, skipPaths ...string) *JWTMiddleware\n109: \n110: // Middleware returns the HTTP middleware handler\n111: func (m *JWTMiddleware) Middleware(next http.Handler) http.Handler\n112: \n113: // extractToken extracts the JWT token from the Authorization header\n114: func (m *JWTMiddleware) extractToken(r *http.Request) (string, error)\n115: \n116: // shouldSkip checks if a path should skip authentication\n117: func (m *JWTMiddleware) shouldSkip(path string) bool\n118: ```\n119: \n120: ### 2. JWT Validation (`jwt.go`)\n121: \n122: ```go\n123: // Claims represents JWT token claims\n124: type Claims struct {\n125:     // Subject is the token subject\n126:     Sub string `json:\"sub\"`\n127:     \n128:     // Issuer is the token issuer\n129:     Iss string `json:\"iss\"`\n130:     \n131:     // Audience is the token audience\n132:     Aud string `json:\"aud\"`\n133:     \n134:     // Expiration time\n135:     Exp int64 `json:\"exp\"`\n136:     \n137:     // Issued at\n138:     Iat int64 `json:\"iat\"`\n139:     \n140:     // Custom claims for AgentCube\n141:     SandboxID string `json:\"sandbox_id,omitempty\"`\n142:     Namespace string `json:\"namespace,omitempty\"`\n143: }\n144: \n145: // Validate validates the JWT claims\n146: func (c *Claims) Validate(now time.Time) error\n147: \n148: // ParseAndValidate parses and validates a JWT token\n149: func ParseAndValidate(tokenString string, publicKey *rsa.PublicKey) (*Claims, error)\n150: \n151: // VerifySignature verifies the JWT signature\n152: func VerifySignature(tokenString string, publicKey *rsa.PublicKey) error\n153: ```\n154: \n155: ### 3. RSA Key Handling (`crypto.go`)\n156: \n157: ```go\n158: // LoadPublicKey loads an RSA public key from PEM-encoded data\n159: func LoadPublicKey(pemData []byte) (*rsa.PublicKey, error)\n160: \n161: // LoadPublicKeyFromBase64 loads an RSA public key from base64-encoded PEM\n162: func LoadPublicKeyFromBase64(base64PEM string) (*rsa.PublicKey, error)\n163: \n164: // ParsePEM parses PEM-encoded data and returns the RSA public key\n165: func ParsePEM(pemBlock *pem.Block) (*rsa.PublicKey, error)\n166: \n167: // GenerateKeyPair generates an RSA key pair for testing\n168: func GenerateKeyPair(bits int) (*rsa.PrivateKey, *rsa.PublicKey, error)\n169: ```\n170: \n171: ### 4. Configuration\n172: \n173: #### Environment Variables\n174: \n175: | Variable | Required | Default | Notes |\n176: |----------|----------|---------|-------|\n177: | `PICOD_AUTH_PUBLIC_KEY` | Conditional | `` | Base64-encoded PEM RSA public key (required if `-auth=picod`) |\n178: | `PICOD_AUTH_MODE` | No | `none` | Authentication mode (`picod` or `none`) |\n179: | `PICOD_AUTH_SKIP_PATHS` | No | `/health` | Comma-separated list of paths to skip auth |\n180: \n181: #### Command-Line Flags\n182: \n183: ```go\n184: // Add to existing PicoD flag parsing\n185: flag.StringVar(&authMode, \"auth\", \"none\", \"Authentication mode: picod or none\")\n186: flag.StringVar(&publicKeyPEM, \"public-key\", \"\", \"RSA public key (base64-encoded PEM)\")\n187: flag.StringVar(&skipPaths, \"skip-paths\", \"/health\", \"Comma-separated paths to skip auth\")\n188: ```\n189: \n190: ### 5. Error Handling\n191: \n192: ```go\n193: // AuthError represents an authentication error\n194: type AuthError struct {\n195:     // Type is the error type\n196:     Type AuthErrorType\n197:     \n198:     // Message is the error message\n199:     Message string\n200:     \n201:     // Underlying is the underlying error\n202:     Underlying error\n203: }\n204: \n205: type AuthErrorType string\n206: \n207: const (\n208:     AuthErrorMissingToken  AuthErrorType = \"missing_token\"\n209:     AuthErrorInvalidToken  AuthErrorType = \"invalid_token\"\n210:     AuthErrorExpiredToken  AuthErrorType = \"expired_token\"\n211:     AuthErrorInvalidSig    AuthErrorType = \"invalid_signature\"\n212:     AuthErrorInvalidClaims AuthErrorType = \"invalid_claims\"\n213:     AuthErrorInternal      AuthErrorType = \"internal_error\"\n214: )\n215: \n216: // HTTPResponse returns the appropriate HTTP status code\n217: func (e *AuthError) HTTPStatus() int\n218: ```\n219: \n220: ### 6. HTTP Response Helpers\n221: \n222: ```go\n223: // WriteJSON writes a JSON response\n224: func WriteJSON(w http.ResponseWriter, status int, data interface{})\n225: \n226: // WriteError writes an error response\n227: func WriteError(w http.ResponseWriter, err error)\n228: \n229: // HealthResponse represents a health check response\n230: type HealthResponse struct {\n231:     // Status is the health status\n232:     Status string `json:\"status\"`\n233:     \n234:     // Timestamp is the current time\n235:     Timestamp time.Time `json:\"timestamp\"`\n236:     \n237:     // SandboxID is the sandbox identifier\n238:     SandboxID string `json:\"sandbox_id,omitempty\"`\n239: }\n240: ```\n241: \n242: ### 7. Integration with Existing Code\n243: \n244: ```go\n245: // SetupHTTPServer creates the HTTP server with JWT middleware\n246: func SetupHTTPServer(picod *PicoD, config *Config) (*http.Server, error) {\n247:     mux := http.NewServeMux()\n248:     \n249:     // Health endpoint (optionally protected)\n250:     mux.HandleFunc(\"/health\", handleHealth(picod))\n251:     \n252:     // Command execution endpoints (protected)\n253:     mux.HandleFunc(\"/api/v1/execute\", handleExecute(picod))\n254:     mux.HandleFunc(\"/api/v1/execute/stream\", handleExecuteStream(picod))\n255:     \n256:     // Apply JWT middleware\n257:     var handler http.Handler = mux\n258:     if config.AuthMode == \"picod\" {\n259:         publicKey, err := LoadPublicKeyFromBase64(config.PublicKeyPEM)\n260:         if err != nil {\n261:             return nil, fmt.Errorf(\"failed to load public key: %w\", err)\n262:         }\n263:         \n264:         middleware := NewJWTMiddleware(publicKey, config.SkipPaths...)\n265:         handler = middleware.Middleware(mux)\n266:     }\n267:     \n268:     return &http.Server{\n269:         Addr:              fmt.Sprintf(\":%d\", config.Port),\n270:         Handler:           handler,\n271:         ReadHeaderTimeout: 10 * time.Second,\n272:     }, nil\n273: }\n274: ```\n275: \n276: ## Impact Analysis\n277: \n278: ### Dependencies\n279: \n280: | Package | Purpose |\n281: |---------|---------|\n282: | `crypto/rsa` | RSA signature verification |\n283: | `crypto/x509` | X.509 key parsing |\n284: | `encoding/pem` | PEM decoding |\n285: | `encoding/base64` | Base64 decoding |\n286: | `encoding/json` | JSON encoding/decoding |\n287: | `net/http` | HTTP middleware |\n288: | `strings` | String manipulation |\n289: | `time` | Time-based token validation |\n290: | `k8s.io/klog/v2` | Structured logging |\n291: \n292: ### Affected Components\n293: \n294: 1. **PicoD HTTP Server** (`code-execution/`): Will integrate JWT middleware into HTTP server setup\n295: 2. **Workload Manager** (`pkg/workloadmanager/`): Will configure auth mode and inject public key\n296: 3. **Code Interpreter Controller** (`pkg/controller/`): Will set `AuthMode` on `CodeInterpreter` spec\n297: 4. **Authentication Service** (external): Will generate JWT tokens for clients\n298: 5. **Client Applications**: Will include JWT tokens in `Authorization: Bearer <token>` header\n299: \n300: ### Backward Compatibility\n301: \n302: - Default auth mode is `none` (no authentication) for backward compatibility\n303: - Existing deployments without `AuthMode=picod` continue to work unchanged\n304: - Public key injection is optional and only required when `AuthMode=picod`\n305: - Health endpoint can be configured to skip authentication\n306: \n307: ### Risk Assessment\n308: \n309: | Risk | Likelihood | Impact | Mitigation |\n310: |------|------------|--------|------------|\n311: | Token forgery | Low | Critical | Use RSA-256/512 signatures, verify with strong crypto |\n312: | Key leakage | Low | Critical | Keys managed by Kubernetes secrets, not in code |\n313: | Token replay | Medium | High | Include `iat` and `exp` claims, use short-lived tokens |\n314: | Clock skew | Medium | Medium | Allow configurable clock skew tolerance (30s) |\n315: | Performance overhead | Low | Low | RSA verification is fast (<1ms per request) |\n316: | DoS via invalid tokens | Medium | Low | Rate limiting, early rejection of malformed tokens |\n317: \n318: ## Alternatives Considered\n319: \n320: ### Alternative 1: Use Existing JWT Library (e.g., golang-jwt/jwt)\n321: \n322: **Approach**: Leverage the popular `github.com/golang-jwt/jwt/v5` library\n323: \n324: **Pros**:\n325: - Battle-tested, widely used\n326: - Handles edge cases (clock skew, token parsing)\n327: - Active community support\n328: - Supports multiple signature algorithms\n329: \n330: **Cons**:\n331: - Additional dependency\n332: - May be overkill for simple RSA verification\n333: - Larger binary size\n334: \n335: **Decision**: Use a minimal custom implementation for simplicity and control, but structure code to easily swap in `golang-jwt/jwt` if needed. The custom implementation will follow JWT standards (RFC 7519) for compatibility.\n336: \n337: ### Alternative 2: Kubernetes ServiceAccount Token\n338: \n339: **Approach**: Use Kubernetes native ServiceAccount tokens for authentication\n340: \n341: **Pros**:\n342: - Native Kubernetes integration\n343: - No additional key management\n344: - Automatic token rotation\n345: \n346: **Cons**:\n347: - Requires Kubernetes API access for validation\n348: - Tightly couples PicoD to Kubernetes\n349: - More complex validation logic\n350: - Not suitable for non-Kubernetes deployments\n351: \n352: **Decision**: Use RSA-based JWT for deployment flexibility and simpler validation. PicoD should work both inside and outside Kubernetes.\n353: \n354: ### Alternative 3: mTLS (Mutual TLS)\n355: \n356: **Approach**: Use mutual TLS for client authentication\n357: \n358: **Pros**:\n359: - Strong security (certificate-based)\n360: - Built into Go's `http.Server`\n361: - No custom token handling\n362: \n363: **Cons**:\n364: - Complex certificate management\n365: - Requires CA infrastructure\n366: - Harder to debug\n367: - Less flexible for distributed systems\n368: \n369: **Decision**: Use JWT for simpler token-based authentication. mTLS is better suited for service-to-service communication at the infrastructure level.\n370: \n371: ### Alternative 4: API Key Authentication\n372: \n373: **Approach**: Use simple API keys in headers\n374: \n375: **Pros**:\n376: - Simple implementation\n377: - Easy to debug\n378: - Low overhead\n379: \n380: **Cons**:\n381: - No standard claims structure\n382: - Harder to distribute and rotate\n383: - No built-in expiration\n384: - Less secure (symmetric keys)\n385: \n386: **Decision**: Use JWT with RSA signatures for better security, standard claims, and asymmetric key distribution.\n387: \n388: ## Testing Strategy\n389: \n390: ### Unit Tests\n391: \n392: 1. **TestJWTMiddleware_ValidToken**: Valid JWT token passes through\n393: 2. **TestJWTMiddleware_MissingToken**: Missing token returns 401\n394: 3. **TestJWTMiddleware_InvalidToken**: Malformed token returns 401\n395: 4. **TestJWTMiddleware_ExpiredToken**: Expired token returns 401\n396: 5. **TestJWTMiddleware_SkipPath**: Health endpoint skips auth\n397: 6. **TestParseAndValidate_Success**: Valid token parses claims correctly\n398: 7. **TestParseAndValidate_InvalidSignature**: Tampered token fails verification\n399: 8. **TestClaims_Validate_Expired**: Expired claims fail validation\n400: 9. **TestClaims_Validate_Future**: Not-yet-valid claims fail validation\n401: 10. **TestLoadPublicKeyFromBase64**: Correctly loads base64-encoded PEM key\n402: 11. **TestLoadPublicKey_InvalidPEM**: Invalid PEM returns error\n403: 12. **TestAuthError_HTTPStatus**: Error types map to correct HTTP codes\n404: \n405: ### Integration Tests\n406: \n407: 1. **TestJWTMiddleware_Integration_FullFlow**: Full HTTP request with valid token\n408: 2. **TestJWTMiddleware_Integration_MultipleRequests**: Multiple concurrent requests\n409: 3. **TestJWTMiddleware_Integration_KeyRotation**: Server handles key change (restart)\n410: 4. **TestJWTMiddleware_Integration_HealthEndpoint**: Health endpoint with/without auth\n411: \n412: ### Test Fixtures\n413: \n414: ```go\n415: // generateTestToken creates a signed JWT token for testing\n416: func generateTestToken(privateKey *rsa.PrivateKey, claims *Claims) (string, error)\n417: \n418: // testClaims returns standard test claims\n419: func testClaims() *Claims {\n420:     return &Claims{\n421:         Sub:       \"test-user\",\n422:         Iss:       \"test-issuer\",\n423:         Aud:       \"picod\",\n424:         Exp:       time.Now().Add(1 * time.Hour).Unix(),\n425:         Iat:       time.Now().Unix(),\n426:         SandboxID: \"test-sandbox\",\n427:         Namespace: \"default\",\n428:     }\n429: }\n430: \n431: // generateTestKeyPair creates a test RSA key pair\n432: func generateTestKeyPair() (*rsa.PrivateKey, *rsa.PublicKey, error)\n433: ```\n434: \n435: ## Acceptance Criteria\n436: \n437: - [ ] JWT middleware correctly validates tokens\n438: - [ ] Invalid/missing tokens return 401 Unauthorized\n439: - [ ] Expired tokens are rejected\n440: - [ ] Signature verification works with RSA public key\n441: - [ ] Configurable skip paths work correctly\n442: - [ ] Health endpoint can be protected or public\n443: - [ ] Claims are correctly parsed and validated\n444: - [ ] Error types map to appropriate HTTP status codes\n445: - [ ] All unit tests pass\n446: - [ ] Integration tests pass\n447: - [ ] Code coverage >= 80%\n448: - [ ] Documentation includes usage examples\n449: - [ ] Compatible with standard JWT libraries (e.g., PyJWT, jose)\n450: \n451: ## References\n452: \n453: - AR-015: PicoD Command Execution API\n454: - AR-013: Session Storage\n455: - `code-execution/spec.md`: PicoD Specification\n456: - `code-execution/design.md`: PicoD Design\n457: - `deployment/client-go.md`: Kubernetes Client-Go\n458: - `deployment/spec.md`: Deployment Configuration\n459: - RFC 7519: JSON Web Token (JWT)\n460: - RFC 7515: JSON Web Signature (JWS)\n\n(End of file - total 460 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# AR-017: PicoD JWT Middleware\n\n## Purpose\n\nThis proposal implements JWT (JSON Web Token) authentication middleware for the PicoD HTTP daemon in the `pkg/picod` module. The goal is to:\n\n1. **Secure API Access** - Protect PicoD HTTP endpoints with RSA-based JWT authentication\n2. **Token Validation** - Validate JWT tokens signed with RSA private keys using the corresponding public key\n3. **Request Authorization** - Intercept and authenticate incoming HTTP requests before allowing access to command execution APIs\n4. **Flexible Configuration** - Support configuration via environment variables and command-line flags\n5. **Health Endpoint Protection** - Optionally protect the health check endpoint with JWT authentication\n\nThis implementation builds upon the PicoD execution infrastructure established in AR-015 and provides the security layer required for multi-tenant code interpreter deployments.\n\n## Scope\n\n**Module:** `pkg/picod`  \n**Language:** Go  \n**Size:** S\n","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-qwen3.5-plus_20260410T163217Z/AR-017-proposal.md","time":{"start":1775862457652,"end":1775862457669}}}}
